In article <321142334.11628886@vircomm.vircomm.com>, dani.goldenholz@vircomm.com (Dani Goldenholz) writes:
> I read an article in Pop. Mechanics saying that the Clipper chip is being
> petitioned against by some organization...some four letter acronyme...anyway,
> how can I sign?
> 
> It seems that skipjack (Clipper's code) sucks, and that would be bad for the
> U.S. citizens. In addition, it gives the gov. more control than it really
> needs.
> 
> One more question: if I coded my phone call before it entered the clipper
> chip, wouldn't that give me a secure phone line? (and the reciever decodes it
> after exiting of course)

Sure. But Clipper is the "thin end of the wedge."  Once there is an
"government approved (and required)" encryption method, Big Bro will
make all other encryption illegal, or run other encryption vendors out
of business - for your "protection", of course.  Then you have no way to
protect yourself from our rather amoral government.

